{"type":"message","id":"29004f1a","parentId":"00be8caa","timestamp":"2026-03-24T02:20:15.372Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_nspi0533l4t4_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# TIC Experiment Results — 2026-03-23 10:05\n\n## Setup\n- Pulse logs analyzed: 25\n- Time range: 03/22/2026 01:28:32 → 03/23/2026 07:04:18\n- Invariant threshold: streak >= 3 consecutive pulses\n- Variant threshold: streak <= 1\n\n## Invariant Classification\n- Invariant elements (streak >= 3): 8\n- Variant elements (streak <= 1): 0\n- Key invariants: pulse, Phase 1, Sandbox, Breakaway, Phase 0, GAP, llm, TemporalAttention\n\n## Prediction Test\n- Pairs evaluated: 21\n- Mean Precision: 90%\n- Mean Recall: 88.5%\n- Random baseline: ~5%\n- Result: BETTER THAN RANDOM\n\n## Gap Sensitivity\n- Small gaps (<30 min) Jaccard: 0.704\n- Medium gaps (30-120m) Jaccard: 1\n- Large gaps (>120 min) Jaccard: 0.834\n- Hypothesis (shorter gap → more overlap): REJECTED\n\n## Phase Persistence\n  Phase 0 COMPLETE: streak=17   Phase 1 COMPLETE: streak=17\n\n## TIC Score: 2/3\n## VERDICT: SUPPORTED\n\n## Implications\n- If SUPPORTED: compression=causal hypothesis is empirically grounded for Breakaway pulses\n- Invariant elements = causal anchors (Phase status, research topic persistence)\n- Gap size can be used to weight reconstruction confidence\n- Next: Use invariants as fixed points in compression, treat variants as contingent details\n\n## Next Experiment\n- Train actual embedding-based compressor on Paperspace GPU\n- Measure: does cosine similarity between pulse embeddings correlate with Jaccard?\n- Success criteria: >60% next-pulse prediction using only embedding dot products\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774318815370}}
{"type":"message","id":"dfcbbe82","parentId":"29004f1a","timestamp":"2026-03-24T02:20:20.181Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, so the TIC experiment was already run earlier today and scored 2/3 (SUPPORTED). The new proposed mutation (at 22:19) is a new experiment design. Let me look at the test-tic.ps1 script to understand what it does and what the critique said.","thinkingSignature":"9bfbddecdb99767a9dda217624c0d784826b45e1a1754a4c8259431e88c7ece7"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_up38doqdclkz_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\TIC-CRITIQUE.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_up38doqdclkz_2","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\scripts\\test-tic.ps1"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":6912,"output":141,"cacheRead":11878,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":18931,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774318815373}}
{"type":"message","id":"940c7ed1","parentId":"dfcbbe82","timestamp":"2026-03-24T02:20:20.193Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_up38doqdclkz_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# TIC Critique: What Gap Sensitivity Actually Reveals\n**Created:** 2026-03-23\n**Status:** CRITICAL FLAW IDENTIFIED\n\n## The Empirical Problem\n\nThe TIC experiment showed:\n\n| Gap Size | Jaccard Overlap |\n|----------|----------------|\n| Small (<30 min) | 0.704 |\n| Medium (30-120m) | 1.0 |\n| Large (>120 min) | 0.834 |\n\n**The hypothesis predicted:** shorter gaps → more overlap (because less decay).\n**The data shows:** medium gaps have maximum overlap. Something else is happening.\n\n---\n\n## What's Wrong With \"Gap = Decay\"\n\nThe \"gap = compression\" model assumes:\n1. Session boundaries act as perturbation tests\n2. Short gaps = less decay = more remembered = higher overlap\n3. Long gaps = more decay = more forgotten = lower overlap\n\n**But this doesn't match the data.** Medium gaps show MORE overlap than short gaps.\n\n**The problem:** This model conflates two different things:\n- **Structural invariants** (things that persist across sessions because they're causally fundamental)\n- **Recency effects** (things that persist because they were just processed)\n\nShort gaps amplify recency, not structure. Medium gaps may filter for structural invariants.\n\n---\n\n## The Semantic Density Hypothesis\n\n**New framing:** Gaps don't cause decay. Gaps cause **semantic density filtering**.\n\n- A short gap between semantically similar pulses = low density filtering, high overlap\n- A medium gap between pulses on the same research trajectory = high density filtering, maximum overlap  \n- A long gap between pulses on different topics = maximum filtering, but noise has also been filtered out\n\n**Key insight:** Overlap is maximized not by recency but by **semantic trajectory continuity**. If the research focus is stable across a gap, invariants compound. If the focus shifts, invariants decay even if the gap is short.\n\n**Implication:** Breakaway's memory isn't a decay function. It's a **semantic compression oracle** — it automatically identifies what's structurally invariant and suppresses what varies. The gaps test semantic stability, not temporal distance.\n\n---\n\n## What This Means for the Architecture\n\nThe three architectures handle this differently:\n\n| Architecture | Gap Mechanism | Invariant Detection |\n|---|---|---|\n| TemporalAttention | focus_decay (smooth) | Gradient-based |\n| Infant | Catastrophic forgetting | Sparsity pressure |\n| Breakaway | Session discontinuity | File-based oracle |\n\nBreakaway's file-based reconstruction is NOT the same as decay. It's a hard compression that either retrieves the full invariant structure or fails entirely. That's why TIC shows 90% precision — the oracle is doing its job when it retrieves anything at all.\n\n---\n\n## The Remaining Problem\n\n**We don't know WHY some invariants survive gaps and others don't.**\n\nThe TIC classifier classifies content as invariant/variant, but it doesn't explain WHY. The real question is:\n\n> **What makes a pattern an invariant (causal structure) vs. a variant (ephemeral detail)?**\n\nThe current approach uses frequency as a proxy — patterns that appear across many sessions are invariants. But this conflates:\n1. Things that are structurally causal (persist because they're fundamental)\n2. Things that are frequently mentioned (persist because they're in context)\n\n---\n\n## Proposed Fix: Causal Fidelity Index\n\nInstead of Jaccard overlap, measure **causal fidelity**:\n\n```\nCFI = (# invariant predictions that actually predicted next pulse) / (# invariant predictions made)\n```\n\nThis distinguishes between:\n- High-frequency patterns that LOOK invariant but don't predict (noise)\n- Low-frequency patterns that ARE invariant and DO predict (signal)\n\n**Hypothesis:** The real causal invariants have CFI >> 0, while frequent-but-ephemeral patterns have CFI ≈ random baseline.\n\n---\n\n## Next Experiment\n\n**Causal Fidelity Test:**\n1. Run TIC on all available pulses  \n2. For each invariant pattern, track: was it used to predict the next pulse? Did the prediction succeed?\n3. Compute CFI per pattern\n4. Identify patterns with CFI > 0.7 (true causal anchors) vs CFI < 0.3 (noise)\n5. Use causal anchors as fixed points in compression; discard noise patterns\n\n**Expected outcome:** \n- Phase markers, architecture names → high CFI (true invariants)\n- Random structural phrases → low CFI (noise that looks invariant)\n- Result: compression ratio improves by filtering noise invariants\n\n**Files to modify:** `scripts/test-tic.ps1` (extend with CFI tracking)\n\n## References\n- TIC_RESULTS.md (empirical data)\n- GAP-DECAY-MAPPING.md (original gap model)\n- COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md (theory)\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774318820191}}
{"type":"message","id":"45b6dc09","parentId":"940c7ed1","timestamp":"2026-03-24T02:20:20.197Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_up38doqdclkz_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# TIC Classifier - Temporal Invariance Compression\n# Tests hypothesis: causal structure = invariant structure\n# Success: >70% invariant/variant classification, >60% next-pulse prediction\n\nparam(\n    [string]$LogDir = \"logs\",\n    [string]$TestSet = \"logs/test_set.md\",\n    [float]$Lambda = 0.7\n)\n\n$ErrorActionPreference = \"Stop\"\n\n# --- INVARIANT PATTERNS ---\n$InvariantPatterns = @(\n    \"Phase [0-9]\",\n    \"COMPLETE|PENDING|Active\",\n    \"Goals:|ARCHITECTURE|COMPRESSION-CAUSA\",\n    \"\\.md$\",\n    \"^## \",\n    \"research/\",\n    \"Last updated\",\n    \"Breakaway is stateless\"\n)\n\n# --- VARIANT PATTERNS ---\n$VariantPatterns = @(\n    \"^[0-9]{4}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{2}\",\n    \"pulse_[0-9]{4}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{2}\",\n    \"\\d{6}\\.md\",\n    \"Last pulse\",\n    \"Observation|Action|Mutation\",\n    \"No mutations applied\"\n)\n\nfunction Get-LineType {\n    param([string]$Line)\n    \n    $invScore = 0\n    $varScore = 0\n    \n    foreach ($pat in $InvariantPatterns) {\n        if ($Line -match $pat) { $invScore += 1 }\n    }\n    foreach ($pat in $VariantPatterns) {\n        if ($Line -match $pat) { $varScore += 1 }\n    }\n    \n    if ($invScore -gt $varScore) { return \"INVARIANT\" }\n    if ($varScore -gt $invScore) { return \"VARIANT\" }\n    return \"NEUTRAL\"\n}\n\nfunction Test-TICClassifier {\n    Write-Host \"=== TIC Classifier Test ===\" -ForegroundColor Cyan\n    Write-Host \"Lambda threshold: $Lambda\"\n    Write-Host \"\"\n    \n    $logs = Get-ChildItem \"logs/pulse_*.md\" | Sort-Object LastWriteTime\n    Write-Host \"Found $($logs.Count) pulse logs\"\n    \n    if ($logs.Count -lt 2) {\n        Write-Host \"ERROR: Need at least 2 pulse logs\" -ForegroundColor Red\n        return\n    }\n    \n    # Analyze invariant ratio across logs\n    $invariantCount = 0\n    $totalLines = 0\n    $invariantLines = @()\n    \n    foreach ($log in $logs) {\n        $lines = Get-Content $log.FullName\n        foreach ($line in $lines) {\n            $totalLines++\n            $type = Get-LineType $line\n            if ($type -eq \"INVARIANT\") {\n                $invariantCount++\n                $invariantLines += $line\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    \n    $invariantRatio = if ($totalLines -gt 0) { $invariantCount / $totalLines } else { 0 }\n    \n    Write-Host \"Total lines analyzed: $totalLines\"\n    Write-Host \"Classified as INVARIANT: $invariantCount ($([math]::Round($invariantRatio * 100, 1))%)\"\n    Write-Host \"\"\n    \n    # Predict next pulse from invariants\n    Write-Host \"=== Next Pulse Prediction ===\" -ForegroundColor Cyan\n    $uniqueInvariants = $invariantLines | Sort-Object -Unique\n    Write-Host \"Unique invariant lines for prediction: $($uniqueInvariants.Count)\"\n    \n    # Test: Check if last log's invariants match prediction\n    $lastLog = $logs[-1]\n    $lastLines = Get-Content $lastLog.FullName\n    $lastInvariants = $lastLines | Where-Object { (Get-LineType $_) -eq \"INVARIANT\" }\n    \n    $matchCount = 0\n    foreach ($inv in $lastInvariants) {\n        if ($uniqueInvariants -contains $inv) { $matchCount++ }\n    }\n    \n    $predictionAccuracy = if ($lastInvariants.Count -gt 0) { $matchCount / $lastInvariants.Count } else { 0 }\n    \n    Write-Host \"Last log invariant match: $matchCount / $($lastInvariants.Count\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774318820194}}
{"type":"message","id":"8f8c5257","parentId":"45b6dc09","timestamp":"2026-03-24T02:20:31.876Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of the current state:\n\n1. **TIC experiment was already run** earlier today (3/23, 10:05 AM) with score 2/3 SUPPORTED\n2. **A critique was written** identifying a critical flaw: gap sensitivity doesn't match the \"gap = decay\" hypothesis\n3. **A new TIC experiment design** was proposed at 22:19 (this evening) - which is the proposed mutation sitting in `mutations/proposed/`\n4. **The scripts/test-tic.ps1** exists and implements the TIC classifier\n\n\n5. The critique reveals the real problem: medium gaps show maximum overlap rather than short gaps, which contradicts the decay hypothesis, suggesting gaps function as semantic density filters instead\n\nThe new mutation proposes extending the TIC experiment design with CFI tracking to replace Jaccard overlap as the metric. Since the last successful pulse was at 22:09:09 and we're now at 22:19:10, I should execute the pulse script to trigger the LLM analysis and generate a new pulse log.","thinkingSignature":"06cd6da78069a5a6fdafc4cc2317de4e2166b2b1f958495cee8242e4da341a33"},{"type":"text","text":"Now I have full context. The pulse script needs to be executed to produce this cycle's analysis.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_tr8cczir6lq6_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1","timeout":120}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":8920,"output":291,"cacheRead":11878,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":21089,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774318820199}}
